s with and without CPR using\nreceiver operating curves and according to the initial arrest rhythm. Results:\nThere were 230 patients (540 pulse checks) in the training set and 153 patients\n(372 pulse checks) in the test set. Overall 38% (351/912) of checks had a\nspontaneous pulse. The areas under the receiver operating characteristic curve\n(AUCs) for predicting pulse status with and without CPR on test data were 0.84\nand 0.89, respectively. Conclusion: A novel ECG-based algorithm demonstrates\npotential to improve resuscitation by predicting presence of a spontaneous\npulse without pausing CPR. Significance: Our algorithm predicts pulse status\nduring uninterrupted CPR, allowing for CPR to proceed unimpeded by pauses to\ncheck for a pulse and potentially improving resuscitation performance.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 5 Aug 2020 01:38:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-06"}
